hands_on_practices.problem:
A crucial task in quantum information processing is characterizing unknown quantum operations. Consider a scenario where a single-qubit quantum channel is known to be one of two possibilities, chosen with equal prior probability: either an amplitude damping channel $\mathcal{E}_{AD}$ or a phase damping channel $\mathcal{E}_{PD}$. Both channels are described by the same real parameter $\gamma \in [0, 1]$.

The action of the amplitude damping channel on a single-qubit density matrix $\rho$ is given by:
$$
\mathcal{E}_{AD}(\rho) =
\begin{pmatrix}
\rho_{00} + \gamma \rho_{11} & \sqrt{1-\gamma} \, \rho_{01} \\
\sqrt{1-\gamma} \, \rho_{10} & (1-\gamma) \rho_{11}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
where $\rho = \begin{pmatrix} \rho_{00} & \rho_{01} \\ \rho_{10} & \rho_{11} \end{pmatrix}$. This channel models the process of energy relaxation, such as a spontaneous emission from an excited state $|1\rangle$ to the ground state $|0\rangle$.

The action of the phase damping (or dephasing) channel on the same density matrix $\rho$ is given by:
$$
\mathcal{E}_{PD}(\rho) =
\begin{pmatrix}
\rho_{00} & \sqrt{1-\gamma} \, \rho_{01} \\
\sqrt{1-\gamma} \, \rho_{10} & \rho_{11}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
This channel models the loss of quantum information without loss of energy, for example, through random phase kicks.

To determine which channel is present, you are allowed to prepare a single qubit in any state of your choosing, send it through the unknown channel once, and then perform an optimal measurement on the output state. Your task is to find the maximum possible probability of correctly identifying the channel. Express your answer as a function of the parameter $\gamma$.
